# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>Electronic warfare underwent a technical revolution with the arrival of the Clans, as BattleMech sensor capabilities once again rivaled and often surpassed those of the best Star League-era units. In the wake of the liberation of Hesperus II from the Word of Blake, the Lyran Alliance made the development of a dedicated electronic warfare reconnaissance unit a top priority. Utilizing cutting-edge detection and anti-detection technologies, Lyran engineers created the Ghost in 3077, a fifty-ton medium strike 'Mech designed to complement the Griffin in hunter-killer and heavy raiding operations.</p><p>Help from the Duchy of Oriente's Earthwerks-FWL, Incorporated established a second production line on Calloway VI, creating an unusual cross-border partnership. The high cost of stealth components and ongoing legal disputes over the technology have kept production runs relatively small, though both manufacturers offer a simplified variant for open-market purchase.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Ghost is designed around its stealth armor capabilities, many of which were pioneered with the Mongoose II design. Ten and a half tons of Starshield Ultra-Tech stealth armor, powered by a Guardian ECM suite integrated into the Nashan communications system, allow the Ghost to approach targets virtually undetected. A Beagle active probe mounted alongside the Nashan Trac V-102 targeting system provides exceptional detection capabilities, enabling the 'Mech to identify hidden units and defeat enemy electronic countermeasures.</p><p>Powered by a GM 300 XL engine, the Ghost achieves a top speed approaching one hundred kilometers per hour, placing it among the fastest medium 'Mechs in its weight class. Twin Defiance 1002 light particle projector cannons deliver solid damage at respectable ranges, while two Helga Series multi-missile launcher three-packs provide flexible fire support with both long-range and short-range missile loadouts. A BlazeFire Longshot extended-range medium laser serves as a versatile close-range auxiliary weapon.</p><p>While the Ghost does not carry overwhelming firepower, fourteen double heat sinks ensure it can maintain a punishing rate of fire throughout an engagement. The combination of speed, stealth, and electronic warfare systems makes it a fearsome deep penetration raider, capable of dictating the pace and range of any encounter.</p>

deployment:<p>Appearing after Gray Monday in 3133, this field modification of the GST-50 removes the SRM-6 rack and replaces it with an industrial-grade chainsaw, leaving the pair of large pulse lasers as the variant's only ranged weaponry. The modification was driven by the discovery that the GST-50's sensor signature closely mimicked that of a Crosscut LoggerMech, allowing pilots to approach enemy positions under the guise of a civilian IndustrialMech before engaging at close quarters. The reduced logistics footprint from eliminating missile ammunition also proved attractive to commands operating in supply-starved regions during the early Dark Age.</p>

history:<p>The Ghost's development began in the closing stages of the Jihad, when the liberation of Hesperus II from the Word of Blake made the creation of a dedicated electronic warfare reconnaissance unit a Lyran Alliance priority. The design process proved arduous and logistically nightmarish, requiring engineers to corral cutting-edge components from across a fractured Inner Sphere while simultaneously repairing Defiance Industries' war-damaged facilities on Hesperus II.</p><p>An unlikely partnership emerged when the Duchy of Oriente's Earthwerks-FWL, Incorporated reached out to offer aid. In exchange for the rights to produce the Ghost in their own factories, Earthwerks helped the Lyran Alliance acquire and ship the needed parts and labor to finish both the prototype and the main Defiance production line. This symbiotic relationship resulted in all Earthwerks-manufactured Ghosts featuring Lyran power plants, an unusual cross-border supply chain that persisted well beyond the Jihad.</p><p>The Royal Guards regiments of the Lyran Alliance Armed Forces were the first units to receive production Ghosts, and the design quickly became a favorite among Lyran commanders for its ability to disrupt enemy supply lines and command structures. In the Oriente Protectorate, the Ghost was assigned to elite reconnaissance companies within the Fusiliers regiments, where its stealth capabilities proved well-suited to intelligence-gathering operations along contested borders.</p><p>Technological limitations surrounding the construction of stealth armor, combined with an expected but ugly legal battle with manufacturers in the Capellan Confederation over the technology, kept production runs small throughout the design's early history. Both Defiance Industries and Earthwerks offered the simplified GST-11 for open-market sale in an effort to offset the high production costs, and the variant began appearing in military units across the Inner Sphere. Select mercenary commands expressed interest in the Ghost, though fielding one remained a rarity given the limited numbers available.</p><p>By the mid-3080s, Earthwerks undertook an ambitious redesign that produced the GST-50, rebuilding the 'Mech from the ground up with more affordable components to broaden its market appeal. The disruption of Gray Monday in 3133 further drove innovation, as operators began field-modifying the GST-50 with industrial chainsaws to exploit the variant's sensor signature resemblance to civilian Crosscut LoggerMechs, adding a deceptive edge to an already stealthy lineage.</p>

